definition: "Dihydrotestosterone (DHT) is a potent androgen produced from testosterone by the enzyme 5α-reductase, which is highly expressed in skin, hair follicles, the prostate, liver, and the urogenital sinus. DHT binds to the androgen receptor with approximately 3–10 times the affinity of testosterone and dissociates from the receptor more slowly, producing a more prolonged and powerful androgenic signal. Unlike testosterone, DHT cannot be aromatized to estrogen, making it a pure androgenic agent without estrogenic counterbalance. DHT is responsible for several critical developmental and physiological processes: virilization of the external genitalia during fetal development, prostate development, androgenic hair patterns (beard, body hair), male pattern baldness (paradoxically), and aspects of sebaceous gland function. The 5α-reductase enzyme exists in two primary isoforms: type 1 (expressed primarily in skin, scalp, and liver) and type 2 (expressed primarily in the prostate, genital skin, and liver). 5α-reductase inhibitors (finasteride, dutasteride) — drugs used to treat benign prostatic hyperplasia and androgenic alopecia — block one or both isoforms and substantially reduce DHT levels."
why_it_matters: "DHT occupies a uniquely polarized position in men's health: it drives androgenic hair loss and prostate enlargement — two of the most common age-related conditions in men — while also being essential for male sexual differentiation, libido, and aspects of cognitive function in some contexts. For men in hormonal optimization programs, DHT is a critical safety and efficacy marker. Testosterone therapy (TRT) increases both testosterone and, through 5α-reductase conversion, DHT. The magnitude of this DHT rise varies substantially between individuals based on 5α-reductase activity, administration route (topical testosterone raises DHT more than injections due to high 5α-reductase activity in skin), and body composition. Elevated DHT is the primary driver of androgenic alopecia (male pattern baldness) in men with genetic susceptibility, and contributes to benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) — the progressive enlargement of the prostate that produces urinary symptoms in most men by their 60s. Understanding baseline DHT and its trajectory on therapy is essential for managing these downstream effects."

